'rslt ← (fun ##.file) fname              ⍝ Apply function to native file tie.⍞000D⍞000DNative file ''fname'' is opened;  the function operand called  with the tie number⍞000Das  argument;  and  the file closed again. The result of the derived function is⍞000Dthe result of the operand function.⍞000D⍞000DTechnical notes:⍞000D⍞000DThe coding is fairly straightforward.⍞000D⍞000D    file←{                  ⍝ Apply operand function to native file tie.⍞000D        tie←⍵ ⎕NTIE 0       ⍝ open file.⍞000D        rslt←⍺⍺ tie         ⍝ operate on file.⍞000D        {rslt}⎕NUNTIE tie   ⍝ close and return result.⍞000D    }⍞000D⍞000DSL suggests the following "crazy" alternative coding:⍞000D⍞000D    file←{⍞000D        ⎕ml←1⍞000D        ⊃⊢∘⎕nuntie\⌽⊢∘⍺⍺\2⍴⍵ ⎕ntie 0⍞000D    }⍞000D⍞000DLocal variables are avoided by duplicating a value to produce a pair and operat-⍞000Ding on each item of the pair in turn. The sequence of events could be represent-⍞000Ded graphically by the following "railway diagram":⍞000D⍞000D     ⊃ ⊢∘⎕nuntie\⌽ ⊢∘⍺⍺\2⍴⍵ ⎕ntie 0         expression⍞000D     ↓   ↓       ↓   ↓   ↓  ↓⍞000D   ──┐├─[⎕nuntie]─┐─[⍺⍺]─┬─[⎕ntie]──        railway diagram⍞000D     └───────────┘└──────┘⍞000D      ↑  ↑        ↑  ↑   ↑  ↑⍞000D      │  │        │  │   │  └───⍵ ⎕ntie 0── opens file and returns tie number.⍞000D      │  │        │  │   └────2⍴─────────── duplicates tie number into a pair.⍞000D      │  │        │  └───⊢∘⍺⍺\───────────── applies ⍺⍺ to second item of pair.⍞000D      │  │        └───⌽──────────────────── swaps the items of the pair.⍞000D      │  └───⊢∘⎕nuntie\──────────────────── unties pair''s new second item.⍞000D      └───⊃──────────────────────────────── extracts pair''s new first item.⍞000D⍞000DExample:⍞000D⍞000D      ⎕nsize file ⎕wsid,''.dws''      ⍝ size of saved version of this workspace.⍞000D217608⍞000D⍞000DSee also: getfile xtabs⍞000D⍞000DIndex:native file|railway diagram⍞000DIndex;Lanzavecchia S.' 
